# Repo-root .dockerignore.
#
# `agent/Dockerfile` and `frontend/Dockerfile` both build with the
# repo root as the build context (`docker build -f agent/Dockerfile .`).
# Without this file, Docker would ship the entire repo to the daemon
# before the first `COPY` runs — including the 1+ GB `.venv` — which
# looks like the build is hung for 30+ seconds before any output.
#
# Per-service `.dockerignore`s under `agent/` and `frontend/` are NOT
# consulted by Docker when the build context is the repo root; only
# this root file is. Treat those per-service files as historical.

# Local virtualenv (huge, slow, never needed in the image — Docker
# rebuilds deps via `uv sync` from pyproject.toml + uv.lock anyway).
.venv/
venv/
env/

# Source control + CI scratch
.git/
.github/
infra/cdk.out/
infra/cdk.context.json

# Caches
__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
.pytest_cache/
.ruff_cache/
.mypy_cache/

# IDE / OS
.idea/
.vscode/
.DS_Store

# Local-only state
.env
.env.*
!*.env.template
*.log
runs/
.bedrock_agentcore/
.bedrock_agentcore.yaml

# Build artefacts
build/
dist/
*.egg-info/

# Other agents' homes don't belong in this repo's images
# (kept here as documentation; this repo only has one agent now).
